This paper is primarily focused on Multi Agent Systems (MASs), which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.MA (Multiagent Systems) sub-category. The paper also discusses the need for agents to interact with each other in a structured and organised manner, which is a key aspect of Artificial Intelligence (AI) research. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely sub-category. The paper proposes a generic architecture for integrating the Agent Conversation Reasoning Engine (ACRE) with different Agent Oriented Programming (AOP) languages, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. The paper also discusses the need for a standard for modelling and sharing agent-focused interaction protocols, which is related to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the benefits of incorporating conversation management into agent programming, which is related to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
